    {
      "id": "aba3e25eb28bc4a2a3f23e6c4b02012b03f4e826",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-04 07:03:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWould it be possible to avoid this patch entirely if rename just dropped the extra FID data if there was no space in the  \"..\" dirent?  This is only needed for upgraded 1.8 filesystems, right?\n\nWhile it definitely makes sense to store FID-in-dirent for normal directory entries, since \"..\" is not as frequently accessed as directory entries it may not be critical for performance to avoid the \"..\" lookups for upgraded 1.8 filesystems.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "df4cf5703cafc34074c34939a449aa80c45b7adb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-04 12:26:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWe can ignore the FID-in-dirent for dotdot entry, since \"..\" is not frequently accessed.\n\nBut this patch \"ext4-dir-dotdot-update.patch\" is used to replace the old patch  \"ext4-hash-indexed-dir-dotdot-update-rhel5.patch\". It is not only for performance, but also for correctness. Because the old patch did not consider the case of rename after MDT file-level backup/restart: there is not enough space to hold the FID-in-dirent. For old Lustre-2.x, rename after MDT file-level backup/restore will either trigger ASSERT() or crash the directory page. The new patch resolve the potential bugs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d5ea4a3d5d7100124c2498e0757777d531350f83",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-04 12:30:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSo we need this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
