    {
      "id": "31a897226b38de2fab3e81f4df749c2af5195423",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-21 17:28:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\nSince we are trying to reduce kernel patches instead if increasing them, I wonder if it makes more sense to just have the osd-ldiskfs code check the \"..\" rec_len to decide if FID-in-dirent will fit, or if the FID data should be dropped? This should be the same as if the dirdata feature were not enabled. \n\nThat would avoid adding complexity to ldiskfs that needs to be maintained fore each kernel, and instead puts it in one place in osd-ldiskfs for every kernel. It would also make it easier to fix this in the 2.1 release, where it also seems to be causing trouble.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "c8071bc1e43e83b9b0c7a2ba1b1464eae172b492",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-01-21 22:37:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/8007f3a6-6418-11e2-b757-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "02e6271e840c55e511895d0696c6706025c8b856",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-22 02:34:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 8:\n\n1) It just replaces the old ldiskfs patch ext4-hash-indexed-dir-dotdot-update-rhel5.patch with the new one ext4-dir-dotdot-update.patch\n\n2) To check the old name entry length for \"..\", we need parse the directory block. Although osd-ldiskfs knows something about the low layer layout, it still some hack, just like parsing ldiskfs directory block in VFS directly. Which makes osd-ldiskfs and ldiskfs more combined.\n\n3) Checking  the old name entry length for \"..\" is OSD layer is not a general requirement. Because zfs backend does not care that.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 8
    },
